metadata.name: Beyond #78
metadata.description:
This generative art token is a collaboration between artist Jaali Bandar and the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. Jaali Bandar‚Äôs genesis fxhash project ‚ÄúMona Lisa Overdrive‚Äù was one of the first NFTs acquired for the permanent collection. It was showcased at the NFT Museum‚Äôs #Cryptografik exhibition throughout the Spring of 2022. 

Jaali Bandar‚Äôs work quickly evolved to become fully immersive and interactive multimedia experiences (see Terra, What on Earth? and Terra Nova). In an effort to bring our worlds closer together, the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC reached out to Jaali Bandar of Bangalore, India to collaborate. This artwork explores the ethereal space where the real and the virtual meet. This is Beyond.  

We share 33% of future royalties with the original minters in an effort to encourage the promotion of fxhash artists and raise awareness of generative art on the blockchain. We want this art to spread far and wide. Thank you for your support in helping us accomplish this goal.


Token Details:

Beyond
Collab by Jaali Bandar x NFTMuseumSC
June 2022
fxhash Compliant NFT


Artist Bio: 

Jaali Bandar is an artist exploring the tech landscape in its anthropomorphic capacity as our collective moves towards a post-human condition. Coming from a design background he is exploring speculative fiction at the interactions of the meta, material and the virtual to create fictional representations using imagery, simulations and experiences.  


Artist Statement

As we let ourselves be overwhelmed by this omnipresent technological feedback, we change rapidly in more ways than we can fathom. As we approach the technological singularity, the question I ask is that how far can we see? As we complete the process of shifting our decision making burdens to the machines, all that remains are automated landscapes of our post-human desires and fragments of memories from a distant past. 

Beyond explores automated human exclusion zones with occasional glimpses of forgotten artifacts of the previous generation as a generative artwork. Diffusion reaction systems have this uncanny ability to morph perspectives as a function of visual feedback loops on the basis of visual inputs with varying degrees of control. 


Interactions:

- Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to show/hide cursor
- Press 's' to save .png 



Additional Credits and Attributions:

- Coded using Cables.gl : https://cables.gl/


About the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC:

Established in October of 2021, the mission of the Non-Fungible Token Museum is to provide a physical and virtual space for NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition in an effort to help our communities benefit from emerging blockchain technologies. Learn more at www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: FairyCells II #175
metadata.description:
FairyCells II is intended as a logical continuation of the first FairyCells series. By dropping the plotter drawing constraint, new perspectives for exploration appeared.
This is how these cells began to intertwine, live together, mutate and change color, like an evolving system.

What surprises me the most in this new series, is the stories appearing behind each new composition. See how these abstracts shapes can come to life and narrate us things through our imagination.

Each color palette takes us into a different world, drawing a very specific atmosphere.

As me, let yourself be carried away by these stories üí´ !

Artwork by Julien_Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: rive #461
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns‚Äìand the comfort we find in them‚Äìin slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

metadata.name: Dencity #177
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Kintsugi #91
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãloss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.
